Speaking to journalists in their offices in Koro, Omoro District on Thursday, Bishop Onweng cited the brutality the police meted out against Forum for Democratic Change party presidential candidate Patrick Oboi Amuriat and the National Unity Platform’s Robert Kyagulanyi, alias Bobi Wine, while on the campaign trail.
“We call upon the Uganda Police Force and its sister forces to enforce the law and order on Opposition leaders with dignity and respect. We condemn in the strongest terms the police brutality on civilians and the frequent use of tear gas, pepper spray, rubber and live bullets while dispersing the crowds of Opposition leaders,” Bishop Onweng said.
He also urged presidential candidates to observe the anti-Covid-19 Standard Operating Procedures. The official Twitter account of the singer-turned-politician also announced the arrest. NTV’s Ali Mivule narrates how he and his colleagues were shot while covering Bobi Wine’s campaign. Pope Francis has accepted his resignation, which came after he attained the mandatory retirement age. Nyeri Town MP Mr Ngunjiri Wambugu said Mr Kang’ata was not sincere in his letter for sharing it with the media and the public. Learning institutions were shut in March to contain the spread of the coronavirus.